    "truncated_text": "I am a private individual strongly opposing the Office of Personnel Management’s proposed regulation – [Docket ID OPM-2025-0004] RIN 3206-AO80.\n\nThe stated reason for the proposed rule is to “allow agencies to quickly remove employees from critical positions who engage in misconduct, perform poorly, or . . .  intentionally [subvert] Presidential directives.”  (Summary 90 FR 17182)  However, this appears to be a thinly disguised effort to impose a “loyalty to President Trump test” for federal employees and fire those employees who are considered not sufficiently loyal to the President.  \n\nThe proposed rule may give “lip service” to the E.O. 14171 “directive” that an employee is “not required to pledge personal loyalty to the President or his policies” (Section 213.3501  90 FR 17201), however, if that employee is classified as “at will” and is fired because, for example, he or she is registered to a political party other than the one currently in office, how does that employee fight that wrongful termination?\n\nThe Summary states that “[a]gency supervisors report great difficulty removing employees for poor performance or misconduct.” (Summary 90 FR 17182).  There is no cite supporting that assertion.  And while making the process easier for supervisors to take adverse actions for employee misconduct may be a worthwhile objective, reclassifying employees in order to strip them of employees’ appeal rights is not logical and from what I have read may not be lawful. The December 2016 publication “Addressing Misconduct in the Federal Civil Service: Management Perspectives”  states at page 3: \n\n“Ultimately, what the survey data indicate is that there is some disagreement among supervisors about how many rights the system should provide to employees, including the desired extent of appeal and grievance rights. But, there is little disagreement on one crucial point – supervisors overwhelmingly want a merit-based system where employees are protected from managers who either make mistakes or act in bad faith. “\nhttps://www.mspb.gov/studies/researchbriefs/Addressing_Misconduct_in_the_Federal_Civil_Service_Management_Perspectives_1363799.pdf   \n\nThe proposed rule does not address the problem of underperforming employees.  Quoting from the OPM Rule “Upholding Civil Service Protections and Merit System Principles”  [Docket ID: OPM-2023-0013]  RIN 3206-AO56 :\n\n“[T]he characteristics of an employee's job—including whether the employee works on policy—has nothing to do with an employee's performance. Schedule F sought to streamline terminations based on the type of work that an employee performs, not based on how well the employee performs. It is therefore difficult to understand how Schedule F can be reconciled with its purported aim of addressing poor performance.”  89 FR 24995\n\nIn my opinion it is not “difficult to understand” how reclassification addresses poor performance, it makes no rational sense whatsoever.  \n\nI am 74 years old and retired.  I receive Social Security based on my 40 years of work and rely on Medicare for health insurance coverage.  It is very important to me that the Social Security Administration employs reliable, knowledgeable employees and that human beings in the office are accessible by telephone, in person and online.  \n\nI have always paid my taxes and believe that it is a responsibility of everyone who lives in this country to pay his or her fair share of taxes.  I rely on the Internal Revenue Service to promptly review my annual returns and promptly issue whatever refund I may be entitled to.  It is important to me that the I.R.S. be fully staffed with reliable, knowledgeable employees.\n\nAs I age, I recognize more and more how important scientific and medical research is for the health of my children and grandchildren.   My family and I will be adversely affected if research is slowed into preventative and curative therapies for respiratory viruses and infections, strok