    "truncated_text": "The suggested policy change will have several major impacts on federal service;\n1) Undermining first amendment rights of federal employees; their ability to register for political parties, engage in constitutionally-guaranteed free-speech activities, and potentially suppress the ability to participate in voting, for fear of punishment. If the intent is to ban federal employees for voting for presidential candidates, or to limit them to voting only for the incumbent, then this should be plainly noted and considered on its face.\n1b) Changing employment status on the basis of political affiliation or beliefs is a violation of state/local law in multiple states, to include Washington, DC. To implement a federal policy such as this would override the rights of states to self-govern, and be an unnecessary and tedious limitation on the freedoms of citizens of those locales. Recommend at minimum limiting the policy change to locations where this would not create a conflict between federal policy and state/local law.\n\n2) CBO analysis shows that on average public employees are paid less than private employees, with an average pay disparity of 24% (https://www.cbo.gov/publication/60235). This pay disparity is partially compensated for by the promise of secure benefits and relatively stable employment. In order to ensure a minimum level of quality service for the American public, should this policy change be approved, it must be paired with tying federal pay to more closely track the equivalent pays in private sector, ideally through an objective measure of pay overall, or by matching pay for similar fields. Inequality of pay has, similar to the limit of supervisory abilities to remove underperforming employees, been a significant concern for adequate staffing for many decades. Solving one issue without resolving the other will result in a significant negative impact to the ability to staff government with qualified and motivated employees.\n\nI appreciate the thoughtful and robust research invested in the policy document in question, and hope the concerns regarding curtailing rights and undermining the basic pillars of effective manpower are resolved expeditiously.",
