    "truncated_text": "I am a scientist and a citizen who is interested in this regulation because I believe that the civil service plays an important role in our society in ensuring that the laws of the land are carried out properly. Specifically, in the context of science, I am someone who has a PhD that was funded, in part, by the National Institutes of Health. I believe that the National Institutes of Health is an institution that has played an enormous role in the success of this country, in allowing for monumental scientific discoveries to be made which are valuable on their own, in addition to contributing to the development of medication (I believe that over 99% of all drugs were developed based on information contained in an NIH funded study) and contributing to the economic activity of this country (I have seen a statistic that says that for every $1 invested into the NIH, the economy recovers $2.46). Therefore, it is important to me to ensure that the National Institutes of Health remains an organization that continues to fund excellent science, in addition to carrying out groundbreaking research within the institute itself.\n\nI would like to comment on the part of this regulation removes protections from civil servants in order to make them easier to fire. I believe that this would be a grave mistake and am opposed to this change. I believe that allowing this change to go through would remove many nonpartisan experts from our federal agencies and would replace them with political appointees. In the context of the NIH, this would be disastrous because it would remove scientists who are renowned in their fields with decades of experience and replace them with political appointees who are interested in carrying out an ideological agenda, namely censorship of research and information that they believe is hostile to right wing causes. In the last months, we have seen the haphazard way in which the National Institutes of Health has terminated many active grants, in fields such as HIV, mRNA vaccines and more. The termination of vaccine-related grants is particularly troubling to me because the skepticism of mRNA vaccines is a result of right wing misinformation and is not based on solid research. I worry that if the NIH continues not to fund many promising areas of research in order to promote a political agenda, the discovery of cures for deadly diseases like cancer and Alzheimers will be delayed. \n\nFurthermore, science is a discipline that requires a lot of training and nuance and replacing experts with novices who are not equipped to make careful scientific decisions will harm the longterm prospects of this country. I know that the rule says that fired civil servants will be replaced with nonpartisans but all of the evidence I have seen so far, does not make me trust the administration when it comes to this statement. For example, the chief of staff of the NIH Director, a position that has always been held by a scientist was recently transferred to Seana Cranston, who is not a scientist but is instead a political operative who has worked with Representative Thomas Massie and Senator Rand Paul. Furthermore, the haphazard nature of the decisions made by the NIH under the Trump administration does not give me confidence that nonpartisan scientists who are fired will be replaced by skilled experts. For example, in an attemot to defund research which is \"DEI\", many important clinical trials testing drugs for diseases like Stage 4 breast cancer have been defunded, simply because they included an LGBTQ participant within the trial. We have also heard of the cancellation of research grants involving domestic partner violence, an issue which affects many women, but which the administration deemed \"unnecessary\" for a reason that is much more likely to be political rather than scientific. \n\nLastly, I am worried that if the status of these civil servants changes to being at-will, then Trump administration officials will be able to fire these employees for speaking out against unlawful orders or acting as whistleblowers. This would severely reduce the autonomy of even nonpartisan experts to carry out their jobs and make decisions that are best for science, even if they are at odds with the wishes of the administration.\n\nTherefore, it is my recommendation that these changes not go through and that civil service protections for civil servants remain in place. \n\nThank you.",
