    "truncated_text": "Dear Office of Personnel Management:\n\nI write to express my strong opposition to the proposed rule entitled \"Improving Performance, Accountability, and Responsiveness in the Civil Service\", published on April 23, 2025. The proposal seeks to exempt a newly defined category of “Schedule Policy/Career” positions from the statutory protections of 5 U.S.C. Chapters 43 and 75, including the right to appeal adverse personnel actions to the Merit Systems Protection Board (MSPB). This proposal is inconsistent with governing federal statutes and exceeds the scope of executive authority.\n\n1. Statutory Protections Cannot Be Waived by Regulation\n\nCongress has clearly and intentionally established a legal framework that governs performance-based and adverse actions affecting federal employees. Under 5 U.S.C. §§ 4303 and 7513, covered employees are entitled to procedural protections, including advance notice, an opportunity to respond, and the ability to appeal to the MSPB. These protections were codified by the Civil Service Reform Act of 1978 (CSRA), which replaced earlier patchwork systems with a unified statutory framework. These rights are not discretionary, nor can they be modified or withdrawn by regulation.\n\nWhile the statute (5 U.S.C. § 7511(b)(2)) allows for the exclusion of certain positions from Chapter 75, such as political appointees or positions designated as “confidential or policy-determining,” it does not authorize the wholesale transfer of career civil service employees into newly created at-will categories through regulatory action. The authority to exclude positions from Chapter 75 is limited in scope and purpose and must be interpreted narrowly to avoid undermining Congress’s express intent.\n\n2. The Proposal Violates the Separation of Powers\n\nBy unilaterally removing procedural protections through the creation of the “Schedule Policy/Career” classification, the Executive Branch is attempting to do through regulation what Congress has expressly prohibited—removing career employees without just cause, due process, or meaningful appeal. This raises significant constitutional concerns under the separation of powers doctrine. The Executive cannot override or nullify Congressional enactments through rulemaking.\n\nThe U.S. Supreme Court has recognized that where Congress has created a comprehensive remedial scheme (as with the CSRA), judicial and administrative bodies must follow that framework. The proposed rule contradicts this well-established principle and risks subjecting the Executive Branch to legal challenge on administrative and constitutional grounds.\n\n3. Undermining Merit System Principles\n\nThe proposed rule would have a chilling effect on the integrity and independence of the civil service. Career employees in policy-influencing roles—many of whom are technical experts or senior supervisors—would become vulnerable to arbitrary dismissal, political coercion, or reprisal for faithfully executing laws as enacted by Congress. This undermines 5 U.S.C. § 2301, which mandates that employees be retained based on performance and protected from arbitrary action and personal favoritism.\n\nRemoving these protections does not enhance accountability—it creates a workforce subject to political influence and fear, contrary to the principles that have guided the civil service for over a century.\n\nConclusion\n\nFor the reasons stated above, I urge OPM to withdraw this proposed rule in its entirety. The authority to alter statutory employee protections rests solely with Congress, and any attempt to circumvent that authority via regulation is unlawful and harmful to the public interest. I respectfully request that OPM reconsider this proposed rule in light of its legal and constitutional infirmities.",
