    "truncated_text": "To: Office of Personnel Management\nRe: Docket ID OPM–2025–0004 – Proposed Rule: Improving Performance, Accountability, and Responsiveness in the Civil Service\nDate: 25 April 2025\n\nDear Office of Personnel Management,\n\nI write in strong opposition to the proposed rule (OPM–2025–0004) that would reclassify federal scientists, statisticians, and other technical experts into the newly created “Schedule Policy/Career” (formerly Schedule F) category, eliminating their long-standing civil service protections.\nAs a Principal Statistician at StatCon Consulting, with over 30 years of experience in biostatistics and data science across academia, industry, and government collaborations, I am deeply alarmed that this rule would make thousands of federal employees at-will—stripping them of due process protections that are foundational to a professional, nonpartisan civil service.\n\nFederal scientists and statisticians play a critical role in ensuring that government policies are grounded in sound, unbiased evidence. Their work touches every aspect of American life—from public health, economic indicators, and climate change to education, agriculture, and civil rights enforcement. These professionals must be free to follow the facts wherever they lead. Reclassifying them as at-will employees introduces unacceptable risks of political interference, data manipulation, and suppression of inconvenient truths.\n\nCounting people, protecting public health, and assessing our economy are not partisan acts—they are civic imperatives. This rule, by making experts vulnerable to dismissal based on subjective notions of \"policy influence,\" undermines the very integrity of our federal workforce and threatens the quality and credibility of the data that inform democratic governance.\n\nMoreover, this proposed rule runs counter to the bipartisan Foundations for Evidence-Based Policymaking Act of 2018, which recognized the vital need for federal data to be collected and used without bias or undue influence. It is not difficult to foresee how this rule would chill scientific speech, reduce retention of federal talent, and erode public trust in government data and services.\nIn a time when evidence-based decision-making is more important than ever, the solution is not to weaken protections for scientists and statisticians, but to reinforce their ability to do their work without fear or favor.\nI respectfully urge you to withdraw this proposed rule in its entirety.\n\nSincerely,\nJesse Canchola, MS, PStat\nPrincipal Statistician\nStatCon Consulting",
    "text_source": "comment",
    "comment_text": "To: Office of Personnel Management\nRe: Docket ID OPM–2025–0004 – Proposed Rule: Improving Performance, Accountability, and Responsiveness in the Civil Service\nDate: 25 April 2025\n\nDear Office of Personnel Management,\n\nI write in strong opposition to the proposed rule (OPM–2025–0004) that would reclassify federal scientists, statisticians, and other technical experts into the newly created “Schedule Policy/Career” (formerly Schedule F) category, eliminating their long-standing civil service protections.\nAs a Principal Statistician at StatCon Consulting, with over 30 years of experience in biostatistics and data science across academia, industry, and government collaborations, I am deeply alarmed that this rule would make thousands of federal employees at-will—stripping them of due process protections that are foundational to a professional, nonpartisan civil service.\n\nFederal scientists and statisticians play a critical role in ensuring that government policies are grounded in sound, unbiased evidence. Their work touches every aspect of American life—from public health, economic indicators, and climate change to education, agriculture, and civil rights enforcement. These professionals must be free to follow the facts wherever they lead. Reclassifying them as at-will employees introduces unacceptable risks of political interference, data manipulation, and suppression of inconvenient truths.\n\nCounting people, protecting public health, and assessing our economy are not partisan acts—they are civic imperatives. This rule, by making experts vulnerable to dismissal based on subjective notions of \"policy influence,\" undermines the very integrity of our federal workforce and threatens the quality and credibility of the data that inform democratic governance.\n\nMoreover, this proposed rule runs counter to the bipartisan Foundations for Evidence-Based Policymaking Act of 2018, which recognized the vital need for federal data to be collected and used without bias or undue influence. It is not difficult to foresee how this rule would chill scientific speech, reduce retention of federal talent, and erode public trust in government data and services.\nIn a time when evidence-based decision-making is more important than ever, the solution is not to weaken protections for scientists and statisticians, but to reinforce their ability to do their work without fear or favor.\nI respectfully urge you to withdraw this proposed rule in its entirety.\n\nSincerely,\nJesse Canchola, MS, PStat\nPrincipal Statistician\nStatCon Consulting",
