    "truncated_text": "**To:** Office of Personnel Management  \n**Re:** Improving Performance, Accountability, and Responsiveness in the Civil Service  \n**Docket ID:** OPM-2025-0004  \n\nI respectfully urge the Office of Personnel Management to withdraw the proposed reclassification rule.  By carving approximately 50,000 positions out from longstanding civil service protections, this change opens the door to politicized firings rather than performance-based actions.  America’s merit system was established to ensure career federal employees can carry out the public’s business free from partisan pressure; stripping these employees of due-process safeguards undermines that core principle.\n\nCareer civil servants play a critical role in maintaining continuity, expertise, and trust across administrations.  When non-supervisory staff fear dismissal for expressing views or implementing policies they believe in, morale and retention will suffer—and the federal government will lose talented professionals to the private sector.  This rule, if finalized, will chill open discourse, encourage loyalty pledges over competence, and discourage qualified individuals from public service.\n\nRather than eroding the neutrality of the federal workforce, OPM should focus on enhancing existing performance-management tools—such as clear, consistent evaluation criteria and robust training for supervisors—while preserving essential appeal rights.  Punitive reclassification is a blunt instrument that fails to address genuine performance issues and instead invites politically motivated dismissals.\n\nFor these reasons, I oppose the proposed rule and request that OPM uphold the merit-based civil service system.  Thank you for your consideration.\n\nRespectfully,  \nChristopher Adams",
