    "truncated_text": "As a civil servant this proposed rule is alarming and detrimental to the operation of our country. With political appointees, there is no need to create this schedule of personnel unless the goal is to create a more partisan civil service. Further, by moving career positions into this new schedule, critical roles that subject matter experts fill (at a far reduced rate than they could get in the private sector) would cease being attractive to leading experts. This will create an overall drain that will put the US behind for decades. Additionally, this rule can create high turnover in positions and subject areas that have historically seen stability. This will lead to repeated loss of agency institutional knowledge which is critical to maintain from one administration to the next to keep the country running smoothly.\n\nHow does this rule protect institutional knowledge at the agencies?\nWhat protections are in place to prevent high turnover in positions that will be rescheduled and no longer have full civil service protections from political action taken against them?\n\nThe guidelines for what positions to reschedule in this rule are vague and can be interpreted by each agency to include few or most of their current civil servant positions. How is this efficient or serving the American people?\n\nIf we are to keep the civil service non-partisan, is this walking back of the April 2024 rule created under the prior administration not a clear example of enacting an agenda based on a partisan agenda? \n\nIf the next administration issues an executive order rescinding this order and eliminating this new Schedule Career/Policy, then are we not now engaged in an ongoing political tug-of-war with the civil service?",
