    "truncated_text": "Good Day,\nI am commenting on the following:\n\n1.  Amending 5 CFR part 213 (Excepted Service) to include Schedule Policy/Career as an excepted service schedule for policy-influencing career positions, while clarifying that Schedule C appointments are exclusively for noncareer (politicall appointments with policy responsibilities.\n\nStatement:\nAllowing career employees to be moved into a new \"excepted service\" category for policy jobs, while calling it an effort to \"increase accountability to the President,\" fundamentally shifts career service away from its nonpartisan mission.\n\nWhy it should not be implemented::\nThis change politicizes career positions that are supposed to serve the American people, not any one President. It erodes trust in the civil service, discourages qualified applicants, and risks the public receiving biased, politically driven service instead of neutral, expert support.\n\n2. Amending 5 CFR part 212 (Competitive Service and Competitive Status):\nStatement:\nLetting employees keep their competitive status \"on paper\" while actually stripping them of competitive service protections undermines both employee rights and the principle of fair, merit-based government.\n\nWhy it should not be implemented:\nThis creates a false sense of security for employees while weakening the systems that protect them from unfair treatment. For the public, it means less stability and independence in the federal workforce, making it harder for agencies to consistently deliver services without political interference.\n\n3. Amending 5 CFR part 752 (Adverse Actions) and part 432 (Performance-Based Actions):\nStatement:\nRemoving due process rights — like appeal protections and performance review procedures — for employees shifted into Schedule Policy/Career roles opens the door to arbitrary firings based on politics, not merit.\n\nWhy it should not be implemented:\nWithout fair procedures, employees can be removed for political reasons,