    "truncated_text": "I oppose the rulemaking, Improving Performance, Accountability and Responsiveness in the Civil Service, and urge OPM and the executive branch not to promulgate this rule in its current form. \nFirst, is this rule in compliance with APA requirements and 12866 interagency review? With such an expedited turnaround from E.O. to proposal, and no substantive discussion on the economic impacts of this rule, which would seem to be significant in terms of potential mass-firings over time, it appears not.\nSecondly, it’s laughable hypocritical that an administration unabashedly dedicated to tit-for-tat patronage in political and staff level appointments (e.g., the DOGE employees selected by Elon Musk, and unelected special employee, now embedded across departments) would pretend to be so concerned with such activities occurring at the lowest levels of government. And the evidence that there are parties attempting to “resist” from within is weak at best, and frankly displays zero understanding of the actual workings of federal agencies, and their dedicated career staff. \nThird, the reliance on a walk through history beginning in the 1800s (when black people were enslaved, women had no rights, and workers would routinely die on the job needlessly due to lack of basic safety requirements) is sad. If you think the 1800s, early 1900s, etc. are the benchmark society that we American citizens want to live in now, please disabuse yourselves of that notion. The forward movement in the laws of the 1960s and 1970s, a time when equality and fairness was finally being paid attention to on a national political level are why those laws should stand, and the protections under those laws via the regulations for civil service protections are good.\nFinally, I do believe that it is difficult to ultimately fire certain employees in the civil service, but I do not believe the issue is with the protections they are offered. Rather, I believe that there is a lack of accounta